      "content": "That is a very common sign of aging, but since you mentioned the plants look \"sickly,\" it could also be a sign of fungal infection or nutrient deficiency. You should check the soil moisture and look for bugs, as root rot and aphids often cause bottom leaves to yellow and drop. It's a good idea to remove those lower leaves to improve air circulation and focus your energy on the new growth. If you're unsure, a quick soil test might help identify if your tomatoes are missing something like nitrogen or potassium.",
