    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the help. i'll try removing the leaves. you mentioned nitrogen though, how would i know for sure if thats the issue? and is there a way to fix the soil so they get more of it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can confirm nitrogen deficiency by looking for pale green or yellowing leaves, especially on older ones, while new growth remains dark green. To fix the soil, you can add compost, aged manure, or a slow-release organic fertilizer to replenish the nutrients. If you're using synthetic fertilizer, be sure to follow the package instructions carefully to avoid burning your plants. Remember, too much nitrogen can actually make the plants look lush but weak, so balance is key. Just like a well-stocked pantry, your soil needs the right mix of nutrients to thrive.",
