    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i'll get some compost. i just hate seeing them look like they're losing all their strength like that. it feels like something is just sucking the life out of them. how do i make sure the nutrients actually stay in the soil and don't just disappear?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That feeling of watching your plants lose their strength is really tough, and it's frustrating when it feels like the nutrients are just vanishing into thin air. You want to lock those nutrients in, right? Well, the best way to keep them in the soil is to add organic matter like that compost you mentioned, which acts like a sponge to hold onto the water and nutrients. You can also try mulching around the base of the plants with straw or leaves; this creates a barrier that stops the wind and rain from washing the nutrients away. It's a bit like building a fort for your soil so the good stuff stays safe and available for your tomato plants to use.\n\nJust remember, even with a good mulch, you might need to add a little more compost every few months as the organic matter breaks down. It's a slow process, but it builds up a really healthy foundation for your plants to grow strong again. Once you get that nutrient balance right, you'll see the bottom leaves stop falling off and the new growth will start looking vibrant and healthy.",
      "source": "target",
